---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { SITE } from '../config';
---

<Base
  title="The Transfer"
  description="The $84 trillion wealth transfer, explained — and why it deserves coverage from the receiving end."
>
  <section class="about wrap wrap--narrow">
    <p class="eyebrow">The thesis</p>
    <h1>Eighty-four trillion dollars is changing hands. Almost nobody covers it from the receiving end.</h1>
    <div class="prose">
      <p class="thesis-lede">
        Between now and 2045, research firm Cerulli Associates projects that
        roughly $84 trillion in U.S. wealth will pass from older generations to
        younger ones — about $72 trillion directly to heirs, with most of the
        rest going to charity. It is the largest movement of money in history,
        and it is already underway.
      </p>

      <h2>Why it matters</h2>
      <p>
        This isn't just a family matter. The transfer will reshape markets:
        which assets get bought and sold, how portfolios are positioned, which
        industries attract capital, and how trillions of dollars think about
        risk, time, and purpose. It will reshape the wealth management industry
        too — studies consistently find that a large majority of heirs leave
        their parents' financial advisor after inheriting. Trillions of dollars
        are about to go looking for new relationships.
      </p>
      <p>
        And it is global. The next generation's wealth won't sit quietly in a
        domestic index fund. Currencies, foreign central banks, trade routes,
        energy markets, and cross-border families all pull on it. That's why
        this letter covers the world economy alongside Wall Street — a
        generation inheriting globally connected wealth needs a globally
        connected view.
      </p>

      <h2>The coverage gap</h2>
      <p>
        Nearly everyone writing about the transfer is on the sending side:
        advisors, estate attorneys, executives, and firms marketing to the
        people giving the money away. The receiving side — the people who will
        actually hold this wealth — is written <em>about</em>, rarely written
        <em>for</em>, and almost never written <em>by</em>.
      </p>
      <p>
        That's the gap this letter fills. I'm on the receiving side of the
        demographic, and I'm training on the professional side of the industry.
        Advisors read it to understand their next clients. Their next clients
        read it to understand what's coming.
      </p>

      <h2>What arrives every Sunday</h2>
      <p>
        Each issue follows the same architecture, so you always know what
        you're getting:
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>The Week in One Breath</strong> — the week's market action in a
        single paragraph. <strong>Three Things That Mattered</strong> — the
        stories that will still matter in a year, each with a "so what" for a
        long-horizon investor. <strong>The Global Ledger</strong> — one story
        from outside the U.S., because wealth doesn't stop at the border.
        <strong>The Transfer</strong> — the signature segment: one insight on
        the handoff itself. <strong>Chart of the Week</strong> and
        <strong>On Deck</strong> — one picture worth keeping and the events
        that matter next.
      </p>

      <h2>What this letter is not</h2>
      <p>
        It is not investment advice, stock picks, or predictions dressed up as
        certainty. It's education and honest analysis, written by someone close
        enough to the industry to know what matters and close enough to the
        generation to know how it reads.
      </p>

      <p>
        {
          SITE.subscribeUrl ? (
            <a class="btn" href={SITE.subscribeUrl}>Get the Sunday letter</a>
          ) : (
            <a href="/">Read the latest issues →</a>
          )
        }
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
